<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="description" content="CE Blank with Letterhead.dot" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Consultation response on licensing consultation Final October 2010 (3)</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by The Crown Estate</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Crown Estate welcomes this inquiry and would firstly emphasise our support of all the key objectives of the Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009, Marine (Scotland) Act 2010 and Marine Act (Northern Ireland) 2013 including the designation of a network of well managed Marine Protected Areas (MPAs) including the development of Marine Conservation Zones (MCZs):</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcome the opportunity to be further involved in the development of MCZs (MPAs in Scotland) across the United Kingdom in the subsequent stages and associated Impact Assessments;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst we support the process to develop MCZs we believe it is important that the designation process and associated development of management measures are practical, proportional and deliver nature conservation objectives whilst taking into account of other current and future users and uses of the marine and coastal environment;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s a Public Authority, The Crown Estate has a legal duty to consider MPAs when exercising our functions and we have set out in section 3 how we propose to ensure that we have met this duty;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We seek further clarity on the position from the UK Government on when and if Reference Areas will be progressed in England </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as we</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> recognise the extensive work needed in identifying the socio-economic implications within the Impact Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if this option is to progress.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also welcome an update from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Welsh Government on the process for developing MCZs in Welsh waters </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and we welcome the opportunity to be involved in assisting the Welsh Government in the design and delivery of any MPA.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We supported the majority of the (31 recommended) MCZs proposed for designation in the first tranche MCZ consultation in England,  and provided a supportive response to the MPA consultation in Scotland, the MCZ consultation in Wales and the initial strategy for MCZ development in Northern Ireland. </span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Highlighted in our responses is the need to progress the development of management measures for each of the sites developed, for example, with English MCZs we recommend, as a baseline, use of existing management assumptions developed by the regional project groups when these sites were being identified.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Through the various MPA designation processes, The Crown Estate contributed socio-economic data in relation to our role in management of the seabed, as outlined in the introduction below. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission highlights the importance of socio-economic considerations, in particular how these will be addressed in the licensing process and the need for cost effective regulation by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> understanding of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">impacts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">developments may have on the MCZs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and possible mitigations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that could be put in place. This would</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reduce unnecessary burden on developers at the screening and scoping stages and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> also be factored into the development of management measures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would welcome further clarification from UK and Devolved Governments regarding key features of the proposed MCZs/MPAs including the potential association of highly mobile species with the sites and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">how activities outside of the boundaries and related Risk Management Areas (RMAs) will operate. At present uncertainty surrounding these aspects of the proposed designations creates a consenting risk for potential developments that are progressing through the marine planning and licencing process.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We hope that you find this submission helpful and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">constructive. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would be very willing to provide additional information on any of the points we have raised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in this response</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This response is informed by The Crown Estate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s extensive experience of managing activities within the marine environment and, within its core remit, of balancing economic activity with stewardship of natural resources for future generations to use and enjoy. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Crown Estate is in the unique position of managing almost the entire seabed out to 12 nautical miles and having committed a valuable long-term resource to support to the various MPA designation processes, including:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Full resource deployed to attend and support all Regional Stakeholder Groups and sub-groups in England (Finding Sanctuary, Balanced Seas, Irish Sea Conservation Zones and Netgain) over a two year period along with participation in the MPA Sustainability Appraisal Project Advisory Group (PAG) in Scotland and the Technical Advisory Group in the Welsh MCZ designation process. We have fed into the process via attendance at the MPA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">/MCZ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> stakeholder workshops and attended bilateral</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">industry-government meetings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Specific</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> support and advice to UK Government’s Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (Defra) and Welsh Government, Scottish Government and Northern Irish Executive.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Member of Steering Committee of Defra Independent Review of the Evidence for MCZs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Co-ordinator and member of the Sea User Developers Group (SUDG) to develop views and input from seabed industry groups to assist Defra in developing solutions for challenging and complex marine issues.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Crown Estate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, governed by an Act of Parliament,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commercially-run </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">active asset management business</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oversee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a UK-wide portfolio of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> prime urban, rural</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, coastal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offshore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">property</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and land</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In line with our core values, we actively manage these to deliver a c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommercial return, which is paid each year to the Treasury for the benefit of the nation. We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are committed to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">careful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stewardship of the assets we have been trusted to manage.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as a portfolio of urban prime retail and leisure assets, including Regent Street in London, management of the Windsor estate (including Windsor Great Park); our responsibilities extend to managing extensive rural land holdings of around </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">144,000 hectares (356,000 acres) of agricultural land and forests, together with minerals and residential and commercial property</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Our marine and coastal assets comprise of:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our coastal portfolio </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">includes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">around half of the foreshore and beds of estuaries and tidal rivers throughout the UK through which we have interests in ports, harbours, leisure boating and aquaculture facilities. We also own three marinas. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our marine assets include </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">irtually the entire UK seabed out to the 12 n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">autical mile territorial limit and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the sovereign rights to explore and make use of the natural resources of the UK continental shelf, with the exception of oil, coal and gas (this includes marine aggregates and minerals extraction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, offshore renewables and the licensing of cables and pipelines</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">); </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are committed to working with government departments, stakeholders and industry in helping to manage the coastal and marine environment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and acknowledge the important part this designation process has played in this. The Crown Estate supports all the key objectives of the Marine and Coastal Access Act, which includes the designation of a network of well-managed MPAs, and to this end we have provided significant support and data to ensure that the most important sites are recognised and designated. Following designation of MPAs/MCZs, The Crown Estate will continue to be actively involved through the conservation objectives and management measures identification and implementation process. We would welcome the opportunity to be invited by Defra and Devolved Governments to play a key contributing part in the development of the designation process and relevant steering groups going forward as we believe there will be valuable and significant contribution The Crown Estate can make to the designation processes. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Section 3 outlines more specific comments related to the questions posed as part of this inquiry. In particular</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the designation processes to date have given rise to a number of general comments and questions. These apply to the process of designation and management of the MCZ network, but also prompt questions which we feel are important to be considered in the designation and subsequent management of MCZs.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">General comments</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Socio-economic considerations in the licensing process:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mpact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ssessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> prepared as part of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">English MCZ (first tranche </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> indicates strongly that the sites that comprise the first tranche are potentially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">less</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> economically challenging to industry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">than others</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that will be examined for designation at a later stage. It is therefore important to stress at this stage that while many of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">27</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sites </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chosen for designation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may have less socio-economic impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> than many of those not selected, we still have little understanding how socio-economic issues will be addressed during the lic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensing process for development. Through the consultation responses we have made, we have emphasised the importance of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> clarification on this to assist developers and regulators before any future designations are made. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This issue </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of lack of understanding on how socio-economic issues will be addressed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will also become increasingly important as the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regulator’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> guidance for processing licences evolves</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Therefore, we believe engagement with industry/users of the marine environment will be vital as understanding and evidence evolves and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improves.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">What remains unclear, and that we would seek further clarity on,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is what information would be required and how it will be used in the decision making process.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As set out below under the section ‘management measures/options’, further thought is also needed on how management options (presented in the Scottish Government’s consultation) will be incorporated into the licensing process. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Impact Assessment and socio-economic assessment:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> encourage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> efforts to ensure that decisions are made based on the best available evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he legislative basis for the designation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MCZs (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPAs in Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> allows for consideration of socio-economic factors where appropriate. Therefore, where science-based alternatives which meet the objectives of the MPA network have been identified, then we would support the consideration of socio-economic factors in the decision making process. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Impact Assessment and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">socio-economic assessment as part of the Sustainability Appraisal play key role</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the consideration of social and economic factors where science-based alternative exist. The Crown Estate has been actively engaged in the production of these documents through participation on the PAG </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in Scotland, through Regional Stakeholder Groups in England and the Technical Advisory Group in Wales </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provided relevant information and comments to inform this process where appropriate. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Management measures/options:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lack of clarity on the management measures for each of the MCZs/MPAs can contribute to uncertainty from industry, marine users and other stakeholders; therefore, we have welcomed any initial indication of what these might be. For example, the Scottish consultation included management options for the MPAs proposed.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Through the development of management options/measures we would expect them to be practical, proportional and deliver nature conservation objectives without overburdening current and future users of the marine environment. We anticipate that significant liaison will be required with the relevant industries so that their specialist knowledge can inform the development of management measures; this will help to ensure that the measures are feasible and will deliver the required nature conservation benefits.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Crown Estate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">expressed concern through the consultation process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that management measures for MCZs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in England are only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> determined </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">now, following</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> designation. Whil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we appreciate the logic that suggests that management measures cannot be applied until such time as it is clear that the MCZ will be designated, it is difficult for The Crown Estate to comment in detail on many aspects of the way in which designation may affect current activities and future plans without knowledge of the management measures and the impacts they may have. The Crown Estate, al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ong with the Regional Stakeholder G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roups, worked to establish a set of management assumptions that would be applied to a MCZ. The management assumptions were based on the technical understanding of the individuals in the room as well as the best available evidence. The Crown Estate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have encouraged</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that these management assumptions are taken into consideration when the regulators are assessing MCZ impact post designation.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The offshore wind and wave and tidal industries are currently undergoing a period of significant uncertainty and any additional costs can have significant implications for project viability. While we realise that full costings</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are not always possible, we would wish to see that consideration of the implications of management measures is given in terms of project timelines and costs. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">seasonal restrictions on activities could render a project unviable if it prevents construction activity during the summer months.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Interaction with other sectors and other plans: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Scotland, there are a number of overlaps between the draft plan options in the Sectoral Plans for Offshore Wind, Wave and Tidal projects and the pMPAs. One of the mitigations in the Strategic Environmental Assessment for the Sectoral Plans is that “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">designated sites for species and habitats of nature conservation interest should be avoided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”. We do not believe that direct overlap with MPAs should be avoided because we anticipate that there is the potential to achieve co-location between MPAs and offshore renewable energy developments. Potential co-location can be effectively assessed at project level.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It remains unclear from current guidance from the English MCZ process what the consequences will be for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the cable and pipeline industries and this is especially important</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as of the first tranche 27 designated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sites, 19 sites have cables intersecting them or are close enough to be a material consideration. While</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> many sectors such as aggregates and off shore wind energy have invested heavily in determining the potential consequences of their activities, the cable and pipeline industries to date have been largely unaffected by environmental assessment. The consequences of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these designations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emerging guidance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is that there is great uncertainty for both industries on how their activities will be assessed both as existing activities and where new cables or pipelines are planned. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Crown Estate believes it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> important that work is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">carried out</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in collaboration with the industry to establish the scale of the possible impacts of pipeline placement, maintenance and renewal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and incorporates this into a proportionate approach for assessment. The outcome of this would be of significant value in assessing the extent of socio-economic impact which currently must be considered to be underestimated as no costs have been included in the IA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for the first tranche of MCZs in England</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In terms of the aquaculture sector, with respects to the Scottish process, we referred to the targets and aspiration for growth set out in the draft of the National Marine Plan. In order to meet these growth targets, it is possible there will be some pressure to develop within pMPAs and the regulatory process will need to assess aquaculture applications and potential impact on MPAs on a case by case basis.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cost-effective regulation:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Through our consultation responses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> emphasise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the increased understanding of impacts and possible mitigations should be used to reduce unnecessary burden on developers at the screening and scoping stages and this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also be factored into the development of management measures. To assist this move towards more cost-effective regulation, The Crown Estate is eager to help explore acceptable actions and approaches which could be applied to developments to minimise any possible impacts through the use of our extensive experience, data and information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We would welcome involvement in the development of the approach to regulation.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the same vein, where the current understanding of impacts is recognised as being low or negligible, then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we recommend this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be taken into account at the screening and scoping stages of the approval process, especially if effective mitigations can be agreed and applied at an early stage. This is an approach which we would strongly support and it would align with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government’s commitment to better and more proportionate regulation.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Reference Areas:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The English MCZ first tranche proceeded without the inclusion of reference areas in that first round of designation, but it remains important to know what the position is with regard to UK Government’s consideration in future rounds of designation and how potential reference areas will be managed (in particular due to the nature of them meaning all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">extractive, depositional and/or disturbing and damaging activities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are excluded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">). </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We acknowledge that all proposed MCZs in Wales were withdrawn from the 2012 process and we are yet to understand whether the Welsh Government will progress with potentially designating “Highly Protected” MCZs in future. Again, we welcome continued engagement with both Welsh Government and Natural Resource Wales on the development of MPAs.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Crown Estate’s role in managing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MCZs/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Marine a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd Coastal Access Act (2009),</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Marine (Scotland) Act (2010)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Marine Act (Northern Ireland) 2013 all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> identify The Crown Estate as a Public Authority which means that The Crown Estate has a legal duty to ensure that in exercising our functions we must further or (if that is not possible) least hinder the achievement of the co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nservation objectives of MPAs.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In practical terms for The Crown Estate, this means that when we enter into (or change) a seabed agreement, we must consider the potential effects of that agreement on the habitats and species for which MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (MCZs)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have been designated. Where the activity will require a marine licence, then we will usually consider that any potential effects will be addressed sufficiently through the statutory planning process. If the activity will not be licensed through the statutory planning process and we believe that by entering into a seabed agreement there is (or could be) a significant risk to the achievement of the conservation objectives for an MPA, then we have a duty to inform the relevant statutory conservation body and Ministers before we make our final decision about making/changing the seabed agreement. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We trust that you will find these comments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">helpful and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">constructive. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would be very willing to provide additional information on any of the points we have raised above</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">happy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to discuss these matters with you further</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. All of this response may be put into the public domain and there is no part of it that should be treated as confidential.</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Contact:</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background Information on The Crown Estate</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The diverse portfolio of The Crown Estate comprises marine, rural and urban properties across the whole of the United Kingdom </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">valued in total at £8.1 billion (2013 figures). Under</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the 1961 Crown Estate Act, The Crown Estate is charged with maintaining and enhancing both the value of the property and the revenue from it consistent with the requirements of good management. We are a commercial organisation guided by our core values of commercialism, integrity and stewardship. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Crown Estate’s entire revenue surplus is paid directly to HM Treasury for the benefit of UK citizens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2013 this amounted to over £252 million.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our ownership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> comprises virtually the entire UK seabed out to the 12 nautical mile territorial limit, in addition to the sovereign rights to explore and make use of the natural resources of the UK continental shelf, with the exception of oil, coal and gas. We own over half of the foreshore and around half the beds of estuaries and tidal rivers in the United Kingdom. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Crown Estate manages its marine assets on a commercial basis, guided by the principles of sustainable development and social responsibility. We take a consistent approach to the management of our activities around the UK, whilst retaining flexibility to take local factors into account whenever necessary. The Crown Estate can bring to bear an unparalleled level of knowledge and expertise on issues relating to management of the foreshore, the territorial seabed and continental shelf. We have a strong understanding of the needs of a broad range of sea users, as commercial partners, customers and stakeholders. </span></p><p style="font-size:10.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Consolas; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">27 January 2014</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>